## Best Substitute — Micrometer Context Propagation

This is the **most production-grade alternative**, used by Spring Boot 3+ internally:

```xml
<dependency>
    <groupId>io.micrometer</groupId>
    <artifactId>context-propagation</artifactId>
    <version>1.1.1</version>
</dependency>
```

```java
// Register your ThreadLocal as a context value
ContextRegistry.getInstance()
    .registerThreadLocalAccessor(
        "userId",                        // key
        userIdThreadLocal::get,          // reader
        userIdThreadLocal::set,          // writer
        userIdThreadLocal::remove        // cleaner
    );

// Wrap your executor — context auto propagates
ExecutorService executor = ContextExecutorService.wrap(
    Executors.newFixedThreadPool(5)
);

userIdThreadLocal.set("user-123");

executor.submit(() -> {
    System.out.println(userIdThreadLocal.get()); // → "user-123" ✅
});
```

---

## Which Should You Pick?

- **Spring Boot 3+ project** → use **Micrometer** (already bundled)
- **Standalone / non-Spring** → use **Alibaba TTL** (simpler API)
- **Guava only** → manually capture and pass context yourself

---

## Manual Guava Workaround (if you must stay pure Guava)

```java
// Capture context before submitting
String capturedUser = userIdThreadLocal.get();

executor.submit(() -> {
    userIdThreadLocal.set(capturedUser); // manually restore
    try {
        // do work
    } finally {
        userIdThreadLocal.remove(); // always clean up
    }
});
```

Works but is **boilerplate-heavy** and easy to forget. Not recommended at scale.
